entry.title: [DevTools] Correctly restore media type after print preview.
entry.content:
This fixes the issue that LocalFrameView::AdjustMediaTypeForPrinting()

backs up the current media type as follows



```

media_type_when_not_printing_ = MediaType();

```



and MediaType() checks if there is currently a media type override in

place (from DevTools), returns the overridden type if so, and if not

returns the base media_type_. The fix is as simple as replacing the

above line with:



```

media_type_when_not_printing_ = media_type_;

```



to ignore the override, and instead backup the internal state of the

LocalFrameView without being corrupted by a media type override.



Also-By: Andrew Gozzard

Fixed: chromium:760832

entry.title: [infra] Use SSDs for 32-core linux builderless try builders.
entry.content:
The try builders that run on 32-core linux machines all have long build

times. The pool of non-SSD 32-core builderless linux machines is only 4

machines, which can often lead to pending when there are multiple deps

rolls since they often include linux_chromium_cfi_rel_ng,

linux-official, android-official and/or fuchsia-official. The pool of

SSD 32-core builderless try machines often sits unused because it is

primarily used by branch compilator builds. This will switch all of the

try builders targeting linux 32-core builderless machines to request the

ssd dimension to speed them up, then the existing non-SSD machines can

be switched over.

entry.title: [Extensions] Move MatchOriginAsFallback validation to serialization
entry.content:
We validate that, if a script specifies it should use the origin as

a fallback for matching (e.g. in about:blank cases), it doesn't use

match patterns with paths (since these would be meaningless).



Currently, this validation is performed on manifest-specified

scripts and the first time a dynamic script is registered. It is not

used in user script registration or when loading dynamic script

registrations from storage.



Move the validation into script serialization so that it applies to

all relevant sites, and add unittest for script serialization handling

this case.

entry.title: [dPWA] Fix lightweight heap UAF in WebAppCommandManager
entry.content:
Since WebAppCommandManager::StartCommand is added to the end of the

SequencedTaskRunner, other async tasks in the queue can cause a delay

in between where IsStarted() returns true and the command can be

destroyed due to synchronous navigations, leading to the edge case where

a command is set to be started after destruction.



This CL solves that at the low level by making the StartCommand carry

a weak_ptr to a command instead of a raw_ptr, so that destroyed

commands can be filtered out of StartCommand().

entry.title: content/browser: Reuse compositor for subframe navs with RenderDocument.
entry.content:
Reuse LayerTreeView instances in the renderer for subframe navigations

when RenderDocument is enabled. This change adds the browser side code

required for enabling this. The high level changes are as follows:



- Compositing reuse is only done for same-site same-process

navigations.



- An optional FrameSinkId is plumbed through RenderWidgetHost, to

avoid generating a new ID when we're reusing the compositor. The

FrameSinkId is tied to the mojo connections + resources we want to

reuse.



- By default, the renderer side WebFrameWidget is initiated when the

RenderFrameImpl is created. The WebFrameWidget requires initializing

the compositor when its created.

So when reusing the compositor, we defer creating the WebFrameWidget

until commit. This state is now tracked on RenderFrameHostImpl to

defer work which must happen after the renderer side WebFrameWidget

has been created.



- By default, RenderWidgetHostView assumes that its FrameSinkId is

bound to it throughout its lifetime. However when reusing the

compositor, we transfer the FrameSinkId from the old RWHV to the new

RWHV.

RWHVBase now tracks whether its FrameSinkId is bound to it. This is

used to manage ownership of FrameSinkId with both Viz and

RenderWidgetHostInputEventRouter.



Since this is a perf optimization, which

is likely to have issues, this is flag guarded with a default on

switch to ease debugging.

entry.title: Backfill popup heuristic grants when a user is onboarded to 3PCD.
entry.content:
This avoids a stuck state when the following flow occurs:

1. The user is authenticated via a 3P cookie from an IdP.

2. The user onboards onto 3PCD and 3P cookies are blocked.

3. The user returns to the IdP via a popup, but the IdP sees a cookie present so it immediately closes.

4. Since there was no user interaction, no cookie access grants are created for the IdP on the initial site.

5. The user can't sign on until the original cookie expires.



To mitigate this, we are adding the following workaround: when a user onboards, we check for their history of interacting with popups, and backfill the required cookie access grants for the "Popups With Current Interaction" scenario.

entry.title: Deduplicate some WPT.
entry.content:
storagemanager-estimate and estimate-indexeddb are more or less the

same tests, the latter having been ported from the former to use

`async`/`await`. The former probably should have been deleted when the

latter was introduced.



Since some of the tests are related to IndexedDB and some are not, this

change keeps the IndexedDB tests in the file called `estimate-indexeddb`

and keeps the basic tests in `storagemanager-estimate` (with minor

updates).



One wrinkle from the Chromium side is that the behavior of

`storageManager.estimate()` is not actually specced, and as the Chromium

implementation uses LevelDB, which behaves in mysterious ways, adding

things to the database does NOT always increase the reported usage size.

Both of these tests operate on large things, which typically do increase

usage, however we noticed that for one reason or another, the test that

adds an *uninitialized* ArrayBuffer starts failing on Windows if

durability is set to relaxed. There are other ways to make the test fail

as well: using a shorter name for the database, or putting small

values, does not reliably increase the reported usage. This is all fine

in the sense that it isn't defined behavior, but it does suggest that

working in this area or on tests of this ilk is a bit of a minefield.

These tests probably should not exist as WPT, at least not until quota

behavior is specced (see https://github.com/whatwg/storage/issues/110).

But it would also be sort of a shame to delete WPT that are passing, so

I've left them in place for now.

entry.title: [Extensions] Add extensions::ServiceWorkerKeepalive
entry.content:
Extension service workers can have associated keepalives for a

variety of reasons, such as API calls or events. These are currently

implemented through subsequent calls to ProcessManager's

IncrementServiceWorkerKeepaliveCount() and

DecrementServiceWorkerKeepaliveCount(). This means each call site

has to perform those calls, store an associated UUID, and possibly

check the validity of the BrowserContext before decrementing.



Introduce a helper class, ServiceWorkerKeepalive, that adds RAII-style

behavior for this functionality. The ServiceWorkerKeepalive increments

the keepalive count for the associated worker upon construction and

decrements it upon deletion (if and only if the browser context is

still valid).



Use this new struct in ExtensionFunction. Follow-up CLs will use it

in other sites that manually call the Increment/Decrement methods on

ProcessManager.

entry.title: devtools: Support lazy WebFrameWidget creation.
entry.content:
InspectorOverlayAgent is created when a provisional WebFrame is created.

It assumes that the associated WebFrameWidget is initiated when its

created.



The assumption no longer holds true with RenderDocument. Add a probe so

the InspectorOverlayAgent can be notified when the widget has been

initialized and any setup associated with it can be deferred until then.



The change is a no-op if the provisional frame starts with an

initialized widget. So this patch should only have an effect if sub-frame

RenderDocument is enabled.



Bug: 1464791
